<h2>Overview</h2><p>Installing a body lift is an exciting step in customizing your Jeep Wrangler, particularly if you're looking to enhance its off-road capabilities. The JKS 1.25 in Body Lift for the 1997-2006 TJ Wrangler adds crucial tire clearance without compromising the suspension geometry or center of gravity.</p><h2>What This Covers</h2><p>This tutorial will guide you through the installation process of the JKS body lift, including needed tools, step-by-step instructions, and helpful tips to ensure you achieve a secure and efficient setup.</p><h2>Step-by-Step Breakdown</h2><ol><li><strong>Prepare Your Workspace:</strong> Ensure you have a flat, safe area to work on your Jeep. Gather all necessary tools, which include wrenches, a torque wrench, and lubrication for the bolts.</li><li><strong>Disconnect the Fan Shroud:</strong> Start by loosening the bolts that hold the fan shroud. This avoids any potential damage to it during the lift process. Depending on your approach, you can either fully remove the shroud or just loosen it to prevent interference with the fan blades.</li><li><strong>Lift the Body:</strong> With the shroud out of the way, begin loosening the body mounts strategically. Start at the front, particularly around the radiator area, and work your way around, loosening the passenger side first, followed by the driver side. For security, consider swapping in raised motor mounts concurrently to aid in clearance.</li><li><strong>Install Lift Pucks:</strong> Once the body is lifted enough to allow access, insert the lift pucks into the designated mounts. It's crucial to match the correct sizes of bolts as you proceed. Installing the pucks in the right order—starting with the easier ones—can significantly enhance the efficiency of your installation.</li><li><strong>Secure Everything:</strong> Reposition the body back onto the new spacers and begin the process of hand-tightening all bolts. This step is essential for ensuring everything is aligned properly before applying final torque. A personal tip: consider using anti-seize on the bolts instead of thread lock for better future serviceability.</li><li><strong>Adjust Radiator Bumpers:</strong> The final touches include replacing the old radiator bumpers with new, longer ones to accommodate the added height. Lubricate these with a bit of WD-40 to ease the installation process.</li></ol><h2>Helpful Tips</h2><ul><li>Always check the instruction manual that comes with your JKS Body Lift for specific guidance and torque specifications.</li><li>Having an extra set of hands can significantly help during the lifting and bolt tightening stages, especially when dealing with larger lift kits.</li><li>Keep all hardware organized; using labeled containers can save time and effort during reassembly.</li><li>Consider the overall setup of your Jeep regarding additional modifications, such as suspension and drivetrain components, as they may require subsequent adjustments after lifting.</li></ul><h2>Key Takeaways</h2><p>The JKS 1.25 in Body Lift is a fantastic choice for Jeep enthusiasts looking to increase tire clearance while maintaining optimal performance. This installation process not only empowers your vehicle's off-road capabilities but also ensures you have the necessary knowledge and confidence to tackle future mods. Remember, careful preparation and attention to detail during installation will lead to impressive results on the trails!</p>

